/p>\n<ul>\n    <li><strong>Outright Winner:</strong> The classic bet – choose the golfer you predict will win the entire tournament and don the Green Jacket. Odds are typically highest before the tournament starts and adjust in real-time.</li>\n    <li><strong>Finishing Position Bets:</strong> Not sure who will win, but confident a player will perform well? Bet on a golfer to finish in the Top 5, Top 10, or Top 20, regardless of who wins the tournament.</li>\n    <li><strong>Head-to-Head Matchups:</strong> Wager on which of two specified golfers will achieve a better score over a single round or the entire 72 holes.</li>\n    <li><strong>Round Leader:</strong> Predict which player will be leading the leaderboard after the completion of a specific round (e.g., First Round Leader).</li>\n    <li><strong>Prop Bets (Proposition Bets):</strong> These cover unique events within the tournament, such as whether there will be a hole-in-one, a player's total birdies, or the top finisher from a specific nationality (e.g., Top American, Top European).</li>\n    <li><strong>Futures Bets:</strong> Place wagers months in advance of the tournament. These long-term bets often offer greater value as odds may shorten significantly closer to tee-off.</li>\n    <li><strong>Live Betting:</strong> Engage with the action as it happens. Odds shift dynamically during the tournament, allowing you to react to player momentum, course conditions, and real-time scores.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h3><strong>How Masters Odds Are Displayed (American Odds)</strong></h3>\n<p>At FanDuel, Masters odds are primarily shown in the American format. Here's what they mean:</p>\n<ul>\n    <li><strong>Positive Odds (+):</strong> Indicate the profit on a $100 wager. For example, +430 means a $100 bet would win $430 profit, for a total payout of $530. These are typically for underdogs or less favored outcomes.</li>\n    <li><strong>Negative Odds (-):</strong> Show how much you need to bet to win $100 profit. For instance, -150 means you'd bet $150 to win $100 profit, for a total payout of $250. These are usually for clear favorites (though less common in early Masters futures).</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h2><strong>Why Bet on The Masters Odds at FanDuel Sportsbook?</strong></h2>\n<br />\n<ul>\n    <li><strong>Trusted Official Partner:</strong> FanDuel is a legally regulated and trusted sportsbook, offering secure and fair wagering on major golf events like The Masters, backed by official data.</li>\n    <li><strong>Real-Time and Competitive Odds:</strong> Our expert oddsmakers continuously update Masters lines based on live player performance, unique Augusta National course conditions, and market movements, ensuring you get the most competitive pricing.</li>\n    <li><strong>Diverse Golf Betting Markets:</strong> Beyond outright winners, explore a vast selection of Finishing Position bets, Head-to-Head matchups, exhilarating Prop Bets (like Hole-in-One predictions), and dynamic Live Betting options tailored specifically for the Masters.</li>\n    <li><strong>Expert Insights and Educational Resources:</strong> Access valuable data, betting trends, and educational guides to inform your Masters picks, from understanding crucial player form and historical performance to course knowledge at Augusta National.</li>\n    <li><strong>Responsible Gaming Tools:</strong> FanDuel prioritizes your well-being with robust responsible gaming features, including deposit limits, time-outs, and self-exclusion options, always available to ensure your betting remains fun and within your means.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<h2><strong>The Masters Betting FAQs</strong></h2>\n<ul>\n<br />\n    <li><strong>When is The Masters Tournament held?</strong>\n    <p>The Masters Tournament is traditionally held annually during the first full week of April. It is the first of golf's four major championships each year, concluding on Sunday with the presentation of the Green Jacket to the champion.</p>\n    </li>\n    <li><strong>Where is The Masters played?</strong>\n    <p>Uniquely among the major championships, The Masters is always played at the same iconic venue: Augusta National Golf Club in Augusta, Georgia. This consistency builds a rich history and allows bettors to analyze extensive course history for players, which is a crucial factor in handicapping.</p>\n    </li>\n    <li><strong>What is the \"Green Jacket\" tradition?</strong>\n    <p>The Green Jacket is a distinctive single-breasted, three-button blazer awarded to the Masters champion. This tradition began in 1949 with Sam Snead and symbolizes the winner's honorary membership at Augusta National. Only winners and club members are permitted to wear it on the grounds, though champions are allowed to take it home for one year.</p>\n    </li>\n    <li><strong>Do all 72 holes count for my Masters bets?</strong>\n    <p>Yes, for most standard Masters betting markets like Outright Winner, Finishing Position, and Head-to-Head matchups, the bet includes all 72 holes of the tournament (four rounds of 18 holes). Any specific markets that might exclude certain rounds or conditions will explicitly state so in their rules.</p>\n    </li>\n    <li><strong>Can I cash out my Masters futures bet early?</strong>\n    <p>FanDuel Sportsbook may offer a Cash Out option on certain Masters futures bets, allowing you to settle your wager before the tournament's conclusion. This feature enables you to lock in profits or mitigate potential losses, though availability is not guaranteed and depends on real-time market conditions and the specific bet.</p>\n    </li>\n</ul>","canonical":"https://sportsbook.fanduel.com/navigation/pga?tab=the-masters"},"2530":{"id":2530},"2703":{"id":2703},"2716":{"id":2716},"2719":{"id":2719},"3032":{"id":3032}},"defaultScheduledTabs":[],"dimensions":{"jurisdiction":"USA","region":"NJ","language":"en"},"tabs":{"1027":{"id":1027,"title":"Matchups","cards":[{"id":9783},{"id":6581}],"seo":1111},"1030":{"id":1030,"title":"Ho